e intersection of political and theatrical debates, and evolved through a process of trial and error in which certain portrayals of kingship were deemed obsolete and were discarded, while others were promoted as culturally allowable and resonant. In tracing the royal judge’s persistent presence and transformation, Bilis argues that we can better grasp the weighty political stakes of theatrical representations under the ancien régime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFrench drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aFrench dramaxHistory and criticismx17th century. 0aFrench dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJudgment in literature. 0aJugement dans la littérature. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aPolitique dans la littérature. 0aSouveraineté dans la littérature. 0aSovereignty in literature. 0aThéâtre françaisxHistoire et critiquex17e siècle. 0aTragédie françaisexHistoire et critique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 17th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751056540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487510565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487510565.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles